# Migrating `EventProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Problems in the Original Code

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Status | Issue |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Removed entirely — cannot forcibly kill threads |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but **unreliable** | Only interrupts from `WaitSleepJoin` state; race-prone |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Works but **fragile** | Race condition: multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose signals, dequeuing only one item |
| Manual thread management | Unnecessary | `Channel<T>` and `Task` are idiomatic in modern .NET |

### The Race Condition (exists in original too)

```
Thread A: Enqueue("a")  →  Set()
Thread B: Enqueue("b")  →  Set()    ← signal lost, "b" sits in queue
Worker:   WaitOne() → Reset() → Dequeue("a") → WaitOne() ← blocks forever
```

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — drain remaining items if desired
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete(); // signal no more items

        // Give worker time to drain, then force-cancel
        using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        try
        {
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            await _cts.CancelAsync(); // graceful cancellation — replaces Abort()
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(CancellationToken.None);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) => Console.WriteLine($"Processing: {item}");
}
```

---

## What Changed and Why

| Concern | Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) |
|---|---|---|
| **Queue + signaling** | `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` | `Channel<T>` — thread-safe, no manual sync |
| **Worker thread** | `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run` — uses ThreadPool |
| **Shutdown signal** | `Thread.Interrupt()` / `Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + `Channel.Writer.Complete()` |
| **Graceful stop** | `Join(5000)` then `Abort()` | `WaitAsync(timeout)` then `CancelAsync()` |
| **Cleanup** | None | `IAsyncDisposable` pattern |

## Migration Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — This is the #1 showstopper. Replace all `Abort()` calls with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

2. **`Handle()` must respect cancellation** — If `Handle` does long-running work (HTTP calls, DB queries), pass the token through: `Handle(item, ct)`. Otherwise cancellation won't interrupt in-flight work.

3. **Bounded vs. Unbounded channels** — `CreateUnbounded` never applies backpressure. If producers can outpace consumers, use `CreateBounded<string>(capacity)` and switch to `await _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item)`.

4. **Exception swallowing** — The original `RunLoop` crashes silently on any exception. Add error handling in the loop if `Handle` can throw:
   ```csharp
   await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
   {
       try { Handle(item); }
       catch (Exception ex) { Log(ex); }
   }
   ```

5. **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** — Always store and await the task. If you discard it, unobserved exceptions vanish silently.
